  <item>
    <title>A morning in Hampi</title>
    <link>https://geo-traveller.com/2020/04/20/hampi/</link>
    <pubDate>Mon, 20 Apr 2020 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
    <dc:creator><![CDATA[aditya]]></dc:creator>
    <guid isPermaLink="false">https://geo-traveller.com/?p=42</guid>
    <description></description>
    <content:encoded><![CDATA[
      <p>The bus left Hospet at <strong>six in the morning</strong>, while the sky was still that washed-out grey that happens only between Indian summers and the rains.</p>
      <h2>Sunrise on the boulders</h2>
      <p>We climbed Matanga Hill before sunrise. The light came in <em>slowly</em>, as if it had been doing this for nine hundred years and was in no hurry.</p>
      <figure>
        <img src="https://geo-traveller.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/hampi-sunrise.jpg" alt="Sunrise over Hampi" />
        <figcaption>The view from the top of Matanga Hill.</figcaption>
      </figure>
      <blockquote>You could see <em>everything</em> from up there — Vijayanagara, the Tungabhadra, the temple roofs, the road back to the city.</blockquote>
      <h3>What we ate</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Idli at the railway canteen</li>
        <li>Dosa from a roadside cart in Kamalapur</li>
        <li>Pineapple, sliced, from a vendor at Virupaksha</li>
      </ul>
      <p>By noon the heat had settled in. We walked back to the guesthouse the long way, past the elephant stables and the lotus mahal. Visit the <a href="https://hampi.in">official site</a> if you want to plan your own trip.</p>
      <pre><code>Some literal text, preserved.</code></pre>
      [gallery ids="11,12,13"]
    ]]></content:encoded>
    <excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[An early morning hike up Matanga Hill in Hampi, and the long way home through the ruins.]]></excerpt:encoded>
